In just a few weeks, we'll be back here on the 19th of January for the first of the winter lecture series. I'm Steve Bunnell, Director of the College. Tonight's a really special night for lots of reasons. It's a bit of an unorthodox night. We also have a special group of guests, a scout troop here tonight at the front. So give them all a hand. They're here to learn about what we all want to learn about, which is what are people actually really doing? What do young people actually do about sustainability once they get inspired, once they get educated or maybe miseducated, once they get directed to expend their energies out there in the world? So tonight we're going to find out. I'm happy now to introduce the various people who are graduates and students and friends of the College of Sustainability. First, Sarah Aspinall. Sarah. Sarah's from Oakville, Ontario. She's in her fourth year studying Environment, Sustainability and Society in ESS. She's a co-founder and the Research and Development Director of Let's Sprout, which is a group working to facilitate spaces for young girls to increase their authentic leadership capacity and to address environmental and social justice issues. Joanna Brenchley. Joanna's a recent grad from the College of Sustainability in ESS and Environmental Science as well. She has a keen interest in climate justice, healthy communities and public art. She's currently part of CoLab, where she gets to practice research, conduct interactive research and host meaningful conversations with correct pronunciation, all with the aim to support strategic solutions that meet today's complex challenges. And I think CoLab is out there in the audience, aren't they? Where's CoLab? Give it up for CoLab. Yay. Emma Norton. Emma's a graduate of University of King's College with a combined honors degree in ESS and International Development Studies. She was awarded the University Medal in ESS the first one. She is motivated by social justice and climate change and strives for a fossil-free electricity grid in Atlantic Canada, where energy is affordable for all. While at Dal, she was the Sustainability Officer for the Student Union and successfully started a campaign to help students reduce their carbon emissions by traveling by train instead of plane. At the Ecology Action Center, she coordinates the Culture of Efficiency project and was also Manager of Materials and Volunteers for EAC's Showcase Green Renovation project last year. This is a special guy. Rob McNeish. Rob's the Farm Coordinator at Dartmouth North Community Food Center. He's currently building a 20,000 square foot urban farm and community garden. He has a strong passion for food and has been heavily involved in Halifax's urban gardening movement, revitalizing the student garden at Dalhousie while studying sustainability and international development studies. In addition to being a member of the Common Roots Urban Farm since its inception in 2011. Rob's been a long time volunteer with the Community Forest International and in May he will become an alumnus of the College of Sustainability. George is our host. He's a Dal grad who was introduced to the world of youth engagement as a student through a Parks Canada lens. You were proud of moving away from your family to come to Halifax, and I can agree with that. But one of the challenges was remembering that small actions can have a big impact. Not always easy to remember because we turn on the news and everything's huge. I feel you, and I think everyone here can agree. But to complete the sandwich of challenge and pride, one other thing you're proud of is founding Let's Sprout, and you've been on quite a journey. Would you mind sharing a few things with us? Yeah, sure. So for me, when I think about how I got here, I guess it kind of starts in hiring my school, really. I always grew up really caring about environmental and social issues, but I didn't really know how to channel that energy and that passion. And I never really found people to connect with who cared about the same things that I did. And I also had no idea what I wanted to do when I graduated high school. And I kind of accidentally ended up showing up at a presentation that Dalhousie was giving at my high school. And Dal had always been on the back of my mind. I have family from the East Coast, and I spent summers here. I love Halifax. But when I was at this presentation, they were talking a lot about the college, which was something I had never heard about. And I was like, that's cool. That's exactly what I want to learn about. So I applied to Dal and only Dal because I decided that that's all I was going to do, which looking back on it may not have been the smartest decision, but it's fine. It worked out. I'm here. And I got to Dal, and I fell in love with the college from the beginning. I really loved all my classes, and I was finally learning about the things that I wanted to learn about. But I still felt a really big disconnect between the things I cared about and actually how to make tangible action and how to change the things that I wanted to change. So for me, that was a big thing that brought me here.
